We model the remaining 6 stops as bins and the 8 passengers as independent balls placed uniformly into these bins. The bus stops at a stop if at least one passenger chose it, i.e., if the corresponding bin is nonempty.

Let I_j be the indicator that stop j has at least one passenger. Then E[I_j] = 1 − P(bin j empty) = 1 − (5/6)^8. By linearity of expectation, the expected number of stops is 6 × (1 − (5/6)^8).

